CHAPTER II.

THE history of the earlier steps taken in the refounding of the Monastery of Whitby is involved in very great obscurity and beset with much perplexity, not because there are no ancient records treating of the subject, but because these ancient records are so hopelessly inconsistent and irreconcilable with each other, that even a probable approximation to the truth becomes extraordinarily difficult.
